If you’re vegan, please read all the way through.  I have been ordering from this restaurant through Grubhub since May of this year(2020). I was exited when I saw that they had a vegan menu. Things started to go sour when I started noticing real meat in my empanadas and burrito as well using actual meat as a substitute for their vegan meat. Today was the last straw for me. I ordered a burrito which was practically cold. I also ordered Pico de Gallo empanadas and instead received empanadas with meat. I am completely done ordering from this place. I threw away my entire food. And this wasn’t the first time I had to do that. I’m not one of those annoying customers that will call up and demand to have my order replaced, instead I just take the L and move but I’m tired of this.  tl;dr if you’re vegan, don’t order their vegan options because you’ll find actual meat in your order.

I went to a pop up at Navy Yard and decided to give this place a try. Usually, when I am in the area, I try to get my fill of Mexican food. This place was the first to disappoint. First of all, it took a while for my food to arrive. I ordered a queso fundido con rajas (melted cheese with peppers), a dish that doesn't take long to make. The cheese got hard quickly and that's a big no-no. I can't say if the fault is in the cheese quality or the preparation. Could be both. To make matters worse, the restaurant charged me $2 after I asked for more tortillas. The tortillas are not homemade; you can buy a whole bag of the same bland corn tortillas for a $1 at the store. In spite of all this, I give them 3 stars instead of two because the people working there are nice and made the experience somewhat enjoyable. Still, I don't think I'd go back.

It is Christmas Eve day and I did a quick Google search and didn't find anything to be open. Accidently drove by this place and it was the best Mexican I may have ever had. I went with my elderly dad who has strict eating restrictions and they were beyond accommodating. Their salsa had an amazing kick and guacamole was perfect. My dad had the totilla soup which is basically a tomato soup with a bit of cheese and tortillas and fell in love. He even enjoyed the fish. He had the red snapper and we asked the amazing chef to grill it and it came in like a salsa/ veggie sauce...I don't like fish but I would've eaten his whole plate...plus it came with a huge portion of rice and beans. I had steak and cheese enchiladas (butchering spelling) and I sprinkled a bit of guac and salsa on top and it was amazeballs. We also had a light and dark Modelo...go dark!  Then we found out the chef makes 2 of his desserts from scratch...one is a half flan half chocolate brownie cake and the other is tres leches...OMG. We were just gonna stop in for a bite,  but this was perhaps the best dining experience I've had in months. Will travel the 15 min out of my way to go here from now on. Also fell in love with the chef/ owner. He doesn't speak much English but he spoke through his food. His  daughter was our server and had no problem running back 5 times to answer all of our questions. This made our day. Thank You Sir!!!

For some reason when I ask Google to look for Tacos El Maguey, Google constantly brings up Tacos El Mezcal, which is across the street. THIS place is 3917 4th Ave. Do NOT confuse it with the hole in the wall place 3910 4th Ave. El Maguey is leaps and bounds better. Mezcal is okay but the flavors just don't pop. We've tried every variety of taco, burrito, and enchiladas. We have not been disappointed once. Don't let their prices fool you. 3 large tacos will satiated any hungry person. 4 small tacos (only slightly smaller) gives you more variety at the expense of not having a generous dollop of guacamole. I pray this goldmine doesn't get written up in Time Out New York. Also notable is their super clean spacious bathroom which has coat/bag hook.
